| Step | Why it is allowed |
|------|-------------------|
| 1. **Field-level definition** | \(d_I(x,t)\) depends on \(\rho_\varepsilon(x,t)=e^{\varepsilon\Delta}e^{t\mathcal L_f}\rho_0\).  Both \(\partial_t\) and \(\nabla_x\) act freely on this smooth field, so \(d_I\) is differentiable in the classical sense. |
| 2. **Material derivative meaning** | \(\tfrac{D}{Dt}d_I(x(t),t)\) gives the rate of change of \(d_I\) as seen by a fluid particle whose position follows \(\dot x=f(x)\).  Because the limit \(\varepsilon\!\to\!0\) is taken *after* differentiation, the calculation uses only smooth objects and remains well-posed. |
| 3. **Cancellation of \((\nabla s)f\) terms** | Those terms originate from the advective piece \(f\!\cdot\!\nabla_x\); they cancel exactly against the same contribution inside \(\partial_t\).  That is the usual algebra behind the material derivative of any quantity built from \(e^{t\mathcal L_f}\). |
| 4. **Limit in \(\varepsilon\)** | You first form \(\frac{D}{Dt}I_f(x,t,\varepsilon)\), then impose the matched scale \(\varepsilon(t)=\varepsilon_0e^{-2\lambda t}\), and only **after that** take \(T\!\to\!\infty\).  Differentiation and evaluation commute because everything is smooth for every fixed \(\varepsilon>0\). |
| 5. **Notation hygiene** | To avoid confusion with an *ordinary* total derivative, write \(\displaystyle\frac{D}{Dt}\) or \(\mathrm D_t\).  Declare it once (e.g. “Throughout, \(D/Dt=\partial_t+f\!\cdot\!\nabla\)”) and all subsequent uses, including on \(d_I\), are unambiguous. |

